    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-09-25T23:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-09-25T23:00:00-05:00" n="293"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d293">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/8181: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-09-26T12:00:00+08:00"
                            >September 26, 1936—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received September 26—7
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>515. My 513, September 25, 4 p.m.<note n="15" xml:id="d293fn15">Not
                        printed.</note> Japanese naval landing party has still further curtailed its
                    activities and as a result conditions in Hongkew, Chapei and adjoining northern
                    area in Chinese territory are gradually returning to normal.</p>
                <p>Japanese Counselor of the Embassy informed me yesterday evening that the
                    Sino-Japanese negotiations at Nanking had come to a standstill and that unless
                    the Ministers of Education and Industry who flew to Canton yesterday to see
                    General Chiang brought back satisfactory instructions, negotiations would
                    probably be broken off. He also told me that Japanese are taking a very strong
                    attitude but gave no inkling of the nature of their demands.</p>
                <p>Copy to Nanking by mail.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
